{"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"anchor":"Overview","type":"heading","level":2,"text":"Overview"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The beauty of SwiftCrossUI is that you can write your app once and have it look native everywhere. For this reason I recommend using DefaultBackend unless you’ve got particular constraints. It uses "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/AppKitBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on macOS, "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/WinUIBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on Window, "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/GtkBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on Linux, and on "},{"type":"reference","identifier":"doc:\/\/SwiftCrossUI\/documentation\/SwiftCrossUI\/UIKitBackend","isActive":true},{"type":"text","text":" on iOS\/tvOS."}]},{"style":"tip","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"If you’re using DefaultBackend, you can override the underlying backend during compilation by setting the ","type":"text"},{"code":"SCUI_DEFAULT_BACKEND","type":"codeVoice"},{"text":" environment variable to the name of the desired backend. This is useful when you e.g. want to test the Gtk version of your app while using a Mac. Note that this only works for built-in backends and still requires the chosen backend to be compatible with your machine.","type":"text"}]}],"name":"Tip"},{"style":"warning","type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"When using ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"SCUI_DEFAULT_BACKEND"},{"text":" to switch underlying backends, you may encounter some linker-related missing symbol errors. These are caused by a SwiftPM bug and usually disappear if you run ","type":"text"},{"type":"codeVoice","code":"swift package clean"},{"text":" before attempting to 